nIf the test fails in the native image due to the FinalizableReferenceQueue not starting the finalizer thread, I want to figure out how to avoid this issue. In the native image, dynamic class loading with URLClassLoader might throw an UnsupportedFeatureError, particularly regarding the static initialization of FinalizableReferenceQueue. However, it seems like ClassLoader could load the class if it's present. I also wonder about method access and potential null values. It feels like the test drives an agent, and metadata management during the native run could be critical.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning Finalizer Countdown**\\n\\nI need to implement a countdown after the finalizer thread and assert that it waits for 10 seconds. In the native image, the process might be slower, but that should be manageable. To address cases where threadStarted returns false, I want to avoid relying on the internal cleanUp method that might be inaccessible. Instead, I'll create another reference right after enqueueing to help manage this effectively. It’ll be interesting to see how this approach plays out!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_CxTT00UNPrHBQduAzpDGGsPF|fc_0a84fcd2f85ab7760169f4cc8637188191ad6ae194acb82f14", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.jsonwebtoken/jjwt-gson/0.12.0/build.gradle"}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/io.jsonwebtoken/jjwt-gson/0.12.0/build.gradle\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 15202, "output": 1203, "cacheRead": 18944, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35349, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777650803893, "responseId": "resp_0a84fcd2f85ab7760169f4cc74aec48191b8b2fd1519d670dc"}}
